2026-04-21 01:40:47 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module relay contacts or switched-cable indicator branch'] hypothesis_explanation='All module interconnections and polarities are confirmed correct, the PSU is stable and its LED is solid, and the control‑module output cables show a steady ~11.8 V/0 V with no 20‑s dips even while the load lamp clearly extinguishes for about 0.5 s every 20 s. The load module’s diode is effectively shorted and has already been ruled out as faulty; both lamps see a stable ~11 V and work normally when powered. The timing potentiometer and the control IC/oscillator were also replaced with no effect on the symptom. \n\nThis combination of (1) stable supply at the control‑module output, (2) normal lamp behavior when powered, and (3) a persistent brief loss of light that the electrical tests do not resolve, strongly points to an intermittent or oscillatory behavior within the control module’s relay / switched‑cable indicator branch that is not being captured as a full voltage drop in the earlier measurements—e.g., contact bounce, partial opening, or momentary high resistance that interrupts effective current delivery to the lamps without pulling the measured DC voltage fully to 0 V at the probing points. \n\nThus the most plausible remaining root cause is a defect in the control module’s relay contacts or the associated switched‑cable indicator subcircuit (which is in series/interaction with those contacts). Replacing/repairing that relay contact path and its indicator branch should eliminate the periodic 0.5‑second lamp outages while leaving the otherwise steady 12 V rail behavior unchanged.'
