2026-04-21 01:41:02 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['internal lamp indicator branch in load module (small indicator bulb and its wiring)'] hypothesis_explanation='All tests show a rock‑steady ~12 V from the PSU through the control module to the load module, with no dips at the relay outputs, at the load inputs, or at the lamp supply node during the 0.5 s, 20 s‑period blink. The control module power, wiring, relay contacts, timing circuit, and the main lamp and series diode have all either been ruled out via measurement or explicitly replaced without effect. The behavior is reported by the simulator as an internal oscillation/instability, yet only the main lamp is stated in the symptom description as blinking.\n\nGiven that the main lamp’s supply voltage and the control module outputs do not oscillate, the only remaining element that could produce an apparent periodic “off” of the visible lamp, while the electrical conditions remain steady, is an internal load‑module artifact. The most plausible is the **lamp indicator branch** (the small parallel indicator bulb and its wiring). A faulty or intermittently shorting indicator branch could periodically shunt current away from the main lamp or modulate the simulation result so that the main lamp is reported as briefly off, even though the supply rails are stable. Since the main lamp and diode have been ruled good and no wiring or upstream component shows faults, the remaining credible root cause is a defect in the internal indicator-lamp branch (small lamp or its connections) within the load module.\n\nTherefore I suspect the fault lies in the internal lamp indicator branch in the load module (small indicator bulb and/or its local wiring), which should be inspected and repaired/replaced as needed.'
