2026-04-21 01:41:52 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['switched cables indicator branch in control (ambient sensor) module (including its LED, series resistor, and any associated timing/driver subcircuit)'] hypothesis_explanation='All electrical measurements show a rock‑steady ~12 V from the PSU through the control module and into the load module. The relay contacts and control‑module input/output cabling are confirmed good, the timing/sensing IC and timing potentiometer have already been replaced with no effect, the load diode and both lamps (main and small indicator) have been verified or replaced and behave normally, and the PSU battery and LED indicator branch are also verified. Yet the simulator repeatedly reports an unstable/oscillating state, while no actual voltage fluctuation is measurable anywhere along the main power path.\n\nThe only remaining untested active branch in the provided schematic is the “switched cables indicator” branch inside the control (ambient sensor) module: this is the LED and series resistor connected between the switched output node and the return, intended to indicate when the switched cables are energized. If that indicator branch (or any tiny timing/driver circuit associated with it) is faulty—e.g., partially shorted, intermittently drawing current in a nonlinear way, or oscillating internally—it could cause the simulator to detect an oscillatory or non‑convergent state without producing any appreciable voltage sag on the robust 12 V rail feeding the lamp. The load sees a nearly ideal 12 V, so both visible lamps remain solidly on, while only a small internal indicator circuit misbehaves.\n\nGiven that every other plausible component and configuration error has either been ruled out by direct test or by unsuccessful replacement, a fault localized to the switched‑cables indicator branch inside the control module best explains the persistent report of internal oscillation with no observable effect on the main lamp or indicators. Therefore I suspect the switched‑cables indicator LED/resistor/driver subcircuit in the control module as the remaining root‑cause fault.'
