2026-04-21 01:42:46 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient‑sensor module power / ground reference network between 12 V rail and light‑sensor / relay‑drive circuitry'] hypothesis_explanation='All modules and loads show a rock‑steady ~12 V, no real lamp flicker, and every previously suspected active element (battery, relay contacts, timing potentiometer, timing IC, lamps, diode, indicator branches, wiring, terminals) has been ruled out by repair attempts.\n\nThe only persistent anomaly is that the simulator repeatedly flags the control (ambient‑sensor) module as being in an unstable or oscillating state, while at the same time the module’s output to the load remains a stable ~12 V and the relay coil sits with both ends at ~11.85 V. The light‑sensor output / relay‑drive node is around 5.9 V and connected to the coil through ~5 kΩ, indicating that the low‑voltage timing/sensing circuitry is referenced to some internal node that is not cleanly tied to the 12 V / 0 V rails.\n\nTogether with the failed continuity test from the PSU output cables into the control‑module internal supply rails (unresolvable probe nodes on the module side), this points to a fault in the internal power/ground reference network of the ambient‑sensor module: for example, a missing or high‑impedance connection from the 12 V rail to the control IC’s V+ pin, or from the IC’s ground reference back to the true 0 V rail. Such a fault would leave the external switched cable pair correctly and steadily powered (through the relay contact path that is effectively always closed), while the internal low‑voltage sensor/timing section free‑runs or numerically ‘oscillates’ in the model.\n\nThis explains all observations: the lamp and indicators never actually blink (confirmed by direct observation and voltage measurements), the relay contact output is steady, but the diagnostic system still infers a 20‑s, 0.5‑s ‘off’ event due to the unstable internal timing network whose supply reference is faulty. Therefore the root cause is a defect in the ambient‑sensor module’s internal power / ground reference network feeding the light‑sensor and relay‑drive circuitry, not in the load, PSU, or relay contacts themselves.'
