2026-04-21 01:43:05 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module internal ground reference / return path for timing & sensor circuitry (ground pin or trace connection to PSU −)'] hypothesis_explanation='All voltage and continuity tests show a solid 12 V path from the battery through the control‑module relay contacts to the load, and both lamps plus the PSU LED are verified to be continuously ON with no flicker. The relay contacts, timing potentiometer, relay‑drive IC, indicator branches, PSU output terminals, battery, lamps, and load diode have all been tested or virtually replaced with no change in behavior, ruling them out as faults.\n\nHowever, several measurements on the control module’s own supply rails and sensor/drive nodes produce contradictory indications: (1) continuity tests from the PSU output cables into the control‑module internal supply nodes report open circuits / unresolvable nodes, while PSU‑to‑load continuity is good; (2) the control module’s light‑sensor / relay‑drive node is sitting at ~5.9 V relative to “ground,” yet the relay coil terminal is at ~11.85 V with about 5 kΩ continuity between them; and (3) the simulator repeatedly flags the control‑module portion as ‘unstable or oscillating’ even while the load voltage remains stable. These are classic symptoms of the analogue/timing portion of the control module effectively floating with respect to the true PSU negative, i.e., its ground reference is not properly bonded to the system ground.\n\nIf the internal ground pin or trace that should tie the sensor/timing IC and associated components to the PSU − is open or high‑impedance, the relay coil and contacts can still be held in the ON state via some bias or leakage (so the lamp stays powered), but the internal low‑voltage circuitry floats and can exhibit pseudo‑oscillations or non‑convergent behavior in simulation. This explains: (a) stable 12 V at the control output and at the load, (b) the absence of any real lamp‑voltage dips or visual flicker, and (c) repeated reports of an ‘unstable/oscillating state’ confined to the control module even after replacement of all active timing components.\n\nTherefore the most plausible remaining root cause is a fault in the control module’s internal ground reference / return path – for example, a broken ground trace, cracked solder joint at the ground pin of the timing/sensor IC, or an open via that leaves the low‑voltage control circuitry referenced to a floating node instead of the PSU negative. Repairing that ground connection would restore a well‑defined reference and eliminate the spurious oscillatory behavior reported in diagnostics, without needing to replace otherwise healthy components.'
