2026-04-21 01:43:19 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module internal switched‑cables indicator LED branch misconnection (indicator LED and its series resistor wired in parallel with, instead of across, the relay contacts)'] hypothesis_explanation='All electrical measurements show a rock‑steady 12 V from the PSU through the control module to the load module and across both lamps; no 20‑s voltage dips or relay switching are ever observed. Both lamps and the PSU LED are continuously lit when directly observed, so the apparent 0.5‑s ‘off’ event is not due to loss of supply or lamp failure. The relay contacts measure essentially zero drop, and their output is stable. Yet the simulator repeatedly reports an ‘unstable or oscillating state’ tied to the control module and mentions a “switched cables indicator” branch.\n\nGiven that the true hardware elements (battery, PSU LED, relay, lamps, diode, cables, potentiometers, timing IC, grounds) have all been individually tested or hypothetically replaced with no effect, the only remaining plausible root cause within the described system is a wiring/configuration fault of the switched‑cables indicator LED branch inside the control module. If this LED+resistor branch has been miswired so that it is effectively in parallel with the *supply* or relay coil rather than across the switched contacts, it can create an unintended feedback or bias path into the timing/sensor circuitry. This would make the analog network numerically oscillatory (causing the simulator’s non‑convergence and a phantom 20‑s blink report) while leaving the DC level at the load completely steady, exactly matching the observations.\n\nThus the likely root cause is a misconnection of the control module’s switched‑cables indicator LED branch inside the module (a configuration fault of that branch), not a failure of the active components already tested.'
